root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1380</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>axt-001S</fr:addr><fr:route>axt-001S.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Algebraic dcpo</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>25</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="dana-scott.xml"
type="local"
addr="dana-scott">Dana S. Scott</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="source"><fr:strong>Theorem 11.5</fr:strong> of <fr:link
href="dtfofp.xml"
type="local"
addr="dtfofp">Streicher</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  A dcpo <fr:tex>(D,  \sqsubseteq )</fr:tex> is called <fr:em>algebraic</fr:em> if for every <fr:tex>x  \in  D</fr:tex>
  the set <fr:tex>\{ c  \in   \mathcal {K} (D)  \mid  c  \sqsubseteq  x \}</fr:tex> is directed and has <fr:tex>x</fr:tex> as
  its join.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context></fr:context><fr:related></fr:related><fr:backlinks><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1376</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon><fr:addr>axt-002K</fr:addr><fr:route>axt-002K.xml</fr:route><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>D</fr:tex> be an <fr:link
href="axt-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001S">algebraic dcpo</fr:link> and <fr:tex>U  \subseteq  D</fr:tex> a Scott open
  subset. We then have
  <fr:tex
display="block">U =  \bigcup   \{   { \uparrow } c   \mid  c  \in  U, c \  \mathsf {compact}  \} .</fr:tex></fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1016</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:parent>axt-002K</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p><fr:tex>( \impliedby )</fr:tex> This direction follows directly from the <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z">upward
    closure</fr:link> of <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>, which is entailed by its <fr:link
href="axt-001Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Y">Scott
    openness</fr:link>.
  </fr:p>
  <fr:p><fr:tex>( \implies )</fr:tex> Let <fr:tex>x  \in  U</fr:tex>. We need to show that there exists a compact
    <fr:tex>c  \in  U</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>x  \in   { \uparrow } c</fr:tex>. Thanks to the
    <fr:link
href="axt-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001S">algebraicity</fr:link> of <fr:tex>D</fr:tex>, we know that
    <fr:tex>x =  \bigvee ^{ \uparrow }  \{  c  \in   \mathcal {K} (D)  \mid  c  \sqsubseteq  x  \} .</fr:tex>
    The fact that <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="axt-001Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Y">Scott open</fr:link> entails it is inaccessible by
    directed joins so the fact that
    <fr:tex
display="block">\left ( \bigvee ^{ \uparrow }  \{  c  \in   \mathcal {K} (D)  \mid  c  \sqsubseteq  x  \} \right )  \in  U</fr:tex>
    means there exists a compact <fr:tex>c_0  \in  U</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>c_0  \sqsubseteq  x</fr:tex>
    which is to say <fr:tex>x  \in   { \uparrow } c_0</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
